text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!Varia]]%0a%0a!The Beginning of Human Language%0a%0a:Author: BenP%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aIn this article, I discuss something I found about how language as a whole developed and began.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI came across the following article:%0a%0ahttps://www.linguisticsociety.org/resource/faq-how-did-language-begin%0a%0athat discussed how languages begin. It got me thinking about the exact point where the grunts and sounds of prehistoric apes formally became a language. The article details the importance of what it calls "digitized cells," or discrete sounds used to form words, such as consonants or vowels. These, the article notes, were a necessary and key leap forward from a bunch of random sounds to the languages we have today. %0a%0aSince we've recently been talking about syntax, I also think that the order of sounds is necessary to define language itself. I think that even if the apes' grunting itself made no sense, the order of grunting noises that sound differently might have been key to encoding information. For example, a short grunt followed by a long grunt meaning something different from a long grunt followed by a short grunt would be an example of language, I think.%0a%0aAside from this, the article talks about the possible existence of the first genes that made language possible. This certain gene allows for more control of the muscles in the face and head, and its existence might have been the first real step to language. I just found this interesting.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: E:)%0a(:Category: Varia:)
